Russia reopened the Moscow Exchange on Monday after its longest-ever trading halt, resuming trading exclusively in federal government bonds. At the reopening of trading, data from the Moscow Exchange at 10:00 a.m. local time showed that the U.S. dollar had fallen by 3.56% to 101.0925 rubles, while the euro slipped by 6.7% to 107.11 rubles, according to TASS News Agency.